               <msContents>
                  <summary>
                     A complete copy of the <title>Khizānah-ʼi
                        ʻĀmirah</title> (Royal Treasury), originally composed by <persName
                           xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard" role="aut" key="person_90779326"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/90779326/">Ghulām ʻAlī ibn Nūḥ Āzād Bilgrāmī
                           (1704–1786)</persName> in <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1762">1176
                              AH (1762–63 CE)</date> in <placeName type="city"
                                 ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/1140111" key="place_1140111">Aurangabad</placeName>, then
                     capital of the <placeName type="state" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/8698275" key="place_8698275"
                        >Princely State of Hyderabad</placeName>, shortly after his friend and
                     patron <persName role="subject"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/13156856205549600715"
                        key="person_13156856205549600715"><addName type="honourific"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/13156856205549600715"
                           key="person_13156856205549600715">Niẓām al-Mulk</addName> ‘Alī Khān
                        <addName type="epithet"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/13156856205549600715"
                           key="person_13156856205549600715">Āṣaf Jāh II</addName> (b. 1734, r.
                        1762–1803)</persName> ascended the throne.nA major poet and author of
                     several historical and biographical accounts, in this work he relates the lives
                     of some 135 Persian poets with selections of their oeuvre, recounts the history
                     of the Āsaf Jahi dynasty up to his patron, and also covers the reigns of
                     <persName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/139145910119027021680"
                        key="person_139145910119027021680" role="subject">Aḥmad Shāh Durranī (b. 1722, r.
                        1747–1772)</persName> and the <placeName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/138609323" role="subject">Maratha
                           empire</placeName>. Since he lived during many of these events and relates
                     vivid eyewitness accounts, historians deem it a reliable source on <date
                        calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1699" notAfter="1801">18th-century</date>
                     South Asia. One of two complete copies held in the Rylands, this manuscript copied in <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1781" to="1782">1196 AH (1781–82 CE)</date> dates just twenty Islamic years after the author first completed it                             
                  </summary>
                                    <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_925-item1">
                     <author key="person_90779326" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/90779326/">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Bilgrāmī, Sayyid Ghulām ʻAlī Āzād, 1704-1786</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="alt">Āzād</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">بلگرامی، غلام علی حسينی واسطی</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa" type="alt">آزاد</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_890">Khizānah-ʼi ʻāmirah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_890">خزانۀ عامره</title>
                                       <incipit xml:lang="fa"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio 1b):</locus>
                                          سر کلام راجعه حمد صانعیست که انسان را به گوهر گرانمایه ناطقه بنواخت.</incipit>
                                       <explicit xml:lang="ar"><locus from="257b" to="257b"> برگ ۲۵۷پ (folio 257b):</locus>
                                          سبحان ربك رب العزة عما يصفون وسلام على المرسلين والحمد لله رب العالمين.</explicit>
                                       <colophon>Completed in <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1781" to="1782"> 1196 AH (1781–82 CE)</date>.</colophon>
                                       <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                                       <note>For another comeplete copy of this work, see Rylands <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6812"><idno>Persian MS 319</idno></ref>, and for an adridged redaction, see <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6813"><idno>Persian MS 320</idno></ref>. Scholar <persName type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923">Nathaniel Bland (1803-1865)</persName> describes the work in his groundbreaking essay on biographies of Persian poets published in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1848">1848</date>, 
                                          and Naval Kishore Press published the earliest lithographed critical edition in <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1871">1287 AH</date> <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1871">(1871 CE)</date>. For a complete description see Sachau and Ethé's Bodleian Library catalogue, no. 381.</note>
                  </msItem>
